or","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellenor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor  , the result of blending with   Ellen ."]},{"name":"Elenor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]},{"name":"Elinor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Eleanor Millot was born about 1503, in Durham, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Mr Millot and Mrs Millot. She had at least 1 daughter with Richard Marley."},"et":{"Abt 1503–":"umbes 1503–Surnud","1503–Female":"1503–Surnud","1505–1539":"1505–1539","1523–1575":"1523–1575","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1503":"1503","1523":"1523","1575":"1575","about 1523":"umbes 1523","1539":"1539","1505":"1505","Abt 1503":"umbes 1503","Of, Durham, Engl":"Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Gibside, Durham, England":"Durham, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1503–":"noin 1503–Kuollut","1503–Female":"